Evaluating machine learning models

  • Want to build generalizable models
  • Requires strong performance on held-out or test data
  • Need to measure the reliability of the model not solely on the training data

Training, validation, and test sets

  • Split your data into three portions
  • Training
  • Validation
  • Test

Need for the validation set

  • Hyperparameters
  • Hyperparameter tuning
  • Information leaks
  • Only use the test set once, at the end to evaluate the final model

Simple hold-out validation

  • Randomly split the training data one time into two portions
  • Works reasonably well if your dataset is large
  • If the dataset is small, validation and test sets may have too few observations to fairly judge the model

K-fold validation

  • Portion the training data into K partitions of equal size
  • For each partition, train a model on the remaining \(K-1\) partitions and evaluate it on the held-out partition
  • Average across all \(K\) scores to get the final score
  • Works well if the metric has large variance for any given training-validation split

Iterated K-fold validation with shuffling

  • Repeat K-fold validation multiple times, with new K partitions each iteration
  • Generates more precise estimates in a small dataset
  • Computationally intensive

Things to consider

  • Data representativeness
  • Arrow of time

Data preprocessing

  • Convert your data to an appropriate tensor of floating-point numbers (or integers)

Value normalization

  • Rescale your data to a standardized range
  • Avoid large values or heterogeneous values
  • Take small values
  • Be homogenous
  • Standard practice
  • Always calculate normalized values using the training data

Missing values

  • Missingness can be informative
  • No explicit NA value for neural networks
  • Encode missing values as non-meaningful value
  • Over time the network will learn that this means missing value

Feature engineering

  • Unnecessary to create hard-coded transformation of features
  • Why you should still engineer features
  • Engineer features based on your domain expertise

Feature engineering

Overfitting and underfitting

  • Tension between optimization and generalization
  • Underfitting
  • Once generalization stops, model begins to overfit
  • Best solution - get more training data
  • Artificially constrain the quantity of information retained in your model
  • Known as regularization

Overfitting and underfitting

library(keras)
## Warning: package 'keras' was built under R version 3.4.4
imdb <- dataset_imdb(num_words = 10000)
c(c(train_data, train_labels), c(test_data, test_labels)) %<-% imdb

vectorize_sequences <- function(sequences, dimension = 10000) {
  # Create an all-zero matrix of shape (len(sequences), dimension)
  results <- matrix(0, nrow = length(sequences), ncol = dimension)
  for (i in 1:length(sequences))
    # Sets specific indices of results[i] to 1s
    results[i, sequences[[i]]] <- 1
  results
}

# Our vectorized training data
x_train <- vectorize_sequences(train_data)
# Our vectorized test data
x_test <- vectorize_sequences(test_data)

# Our vectorized labels
y_train <- as.numeric(train_labels)
y_test <- as.numeric(test_labels)

Reducing the networks size

  • Reduce the size of the model (capacity)
  • But not too much
  • Best determined via trial and error

Original model

original_model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(10000)) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")

original_model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("accuracy")
)

Smaller model

smaller_model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 4, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(10000)) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 4, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")

smaller_model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("accuracy")
)

Fit both models

plot_training_losses <- function(losses) {
  loss_names <- names(losses)
  losses <- as.data.frame(losses)
  losses$epoch <- seq_len(nrow(losses))
  losses %>% 
    gather(model, loss, loss_names[[1]], loss_names[[2]]) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = epoch, y = loss, colour = model)) +
    geom_point()
}
plot_training_losses(losses = list(
  original_model = original_hist$metrics$val_loss,
  smaller_model = smaller_model_hist$metrics$val_loss
))

Adding weight regularization

  • Occams Razor
  • Applied to neural networks
  • Simple models are distribution of parameters with less variance
  • Weight regularization
  • L1 regularization
  • L2 regularization

Adding weight regularization

l2_model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(0.001),
              activation = "relu", input_shape = c(10000)) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, kernel_regularizer = regularizer_l2(0.001),
              activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")

l2_model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
)

L2 regularization penalty

plot_training_losses(losses = list(
  original_model = original_hist$metrics$val_loss,
  l2_model = l2_model_hist$metrics$val_loss
))

Adding dropout

  • Randomly set to zero a number of output features of a layer during training
  • Dropout rate
  • Deliberately remove data from the layer
  • Why do this?

Adding dropout

layer_dropout(rate = 0.5)
dpt_model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(10000)) %>% 
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.5) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 16, activation = "relu") %>% 
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.5) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "sigmoid")

dpt_model %>% compile(
  optimizer = "rmsprop",
  loss = "binary_crossentropy",
  metrics = c("acc")
)
dpt_model_hist <- dpt_model %>% fit(
  x_train, y_train,
  epochs = 20,
  batch_size = 512,
  validation_data = list(x_test, y_test)
)

Adding dropout

plot_training_losses(losses = list(
  original_model = original_hist$metrics$val_loss,
  dpt_model = dpt_model_hist$metrics$val_loss
))

Universal workflow of machine learning

  1. Define the problem and assemble a dataset
  2. Choose a measure of success
  3. Decide on an evaluation protocol
  4. Prepare your data
  5. Develop a model that performs better than the baseline
  6. Develop a model that overfits
  7. Regularize your model and tune your hyperparameters
  8. Retrain a final time on all training data and evaluate using the test data
